│ It seems my previous fix was incomplete. I only addressed    │
│ the `and` version of the power-of-two check (`x != 0 &&      │
│ ctpop(x) < 2`), but the test failure shows that the `or`     │
│ version (`x == 0 || ctpop(x) > 1`) has the exact same bug.   │
│                                                              │
│ ### Analysis of the New Failure                              │
│                                                              │
│ *   **Failing Code**: The test case `has_single_bit_inv`     │
│ implements `(x == 0) || (ctpop(x) > 1)`.                     │
│ *   **The Flawed Transformation**: The optimizer transforms  │
│ this into `ctpop(x) != 1`.                                   │
│ *   **The `poison` Problem**: Just like before, when `x` is  │
│ 0, the original expression evaluates to `true` because the   │
│ first part of the `||` is true, and the `ctpop` is never     │
│ evaluated. However, in the transformed code, `ctpop(0)` with │
│ the `range(1, 33)` metadata becomes `poison`, and `icmp ne   │
│ poison, 1` is also `poison`.                                 │
│ *   **Incorrect Result**: A concrete `true` value is turned  │
│ into `poison`, which is a miscompilation.                    │
│ *   **Root Cause**: The transformation for the `or` case in  │
│ `foldIsPowerOf2` also fails to consider the `poison`-on-zero │
│ behavior of `ctpop` with range metadata. It needs the same   │
│ `noundef` guard as the `and` case.                           │
│                                                              │
│ ### Proposed Fix                                             │
│                                                              │
│ I will apply the same `noundef` check to the second part of  │
│ the `foldIsPowerOf2` function, which handles the `or` logic. │
│ This will ensure both transformations are safe.              │
